{
  "query": "What are the benefits for butterflies of maintaining species-rich, semi-natural grasslands compared to using set-aside in European agricultural landscapes?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, species-rich, semi-natural grasslands provide superior butterfly conservation benefits compared to set-aside areas in European agricultural landscapes. \n\nSpecies-rich, semi-natural grasslands maintained through traditional management (light grazing or annual mowing) consistently showed higher butterfly species richness and abundance compared to set-aside areas. One replicated study from Hungary found that semi-natural grasslands managed by either light grazing or mowing once/year in May or June had a higher abundance of butterflies than conventional wheat fields (action 3908). Multiple European studies demonstrated that old meadows managed through traditional practices had higher species richness of adult butterflies and caterpillars than recently established set-aside areas (action 3908).\n\nSet-aside areas, while showing some benefits over intensive arable farming, had mixed results for butterfly conservation. Studies found that set-aside fields had similar abundance of butterfly and moth adults and caterpillars to uncultivated field boundaries and extensively farmed land (action 3980), but did not consistently outperform semi-natural grasslands. While some set-aside areas sown with less competitive grasses showed higher butterfly abundance than cereal fields, they did not match the conservation value of established species-rich grasslands (action 3980).\n\nThe research demonstrates that restored grasslands from arable land can achieve similar or higher abundance of moths compared to conventional grasslands, but the time since restoration and seed mix composition significantly affects outcomes (action 3929). In contrast, long-established species-rich, semi-natural grasslands maintained through traditional management practices consistently provided more reliable and superior habitat for butterfly communities across multiple European studies.",
